description.text: This is a basic assembled mockup of the MPhone modular phone.

J.J. Thomson (1904) asked: How do a small number of electrons arrange themselves on the surface of a unit sphere? Solutions have been proposed for cases where the number of electrons varies from 2 to 400 and beyond. However few solutions have been proved to be optimal. Two types of polyhedra are useful for those working on the problem; the convex hull and its dual. A nice applet from Syracuse University shows virtual versions of these polyhedra. (Run http://thomson.phy.syr.edu/thomsonapplet.php
Type n = 11 into the applet and press start - one can then alternate between the convex hull, "mesh", and its dual, "dual".) It would be nice to print physical versions of these polyhedra and it was suggested to me that qhull - http://www.qhull.org/ - outputs these polyhedra in a simple format called OFF. I was able to write a program that coverts OFF format to openSCAD polyhedron commands. Coordinates for possible solutions to the Thomson problem are available at The Cambridge Cluster Database http://www-wales.ch.cam.ac.uk/~wales/CCD/Thomson/table.html Solutions for n=10, 11, 13, and 14 were downloaded and converted to polyhedron commands. Additionally an openSCAD program used to make Christmas ornaments, thing:14337, needed little modification to show the positions of the electrons as stars on the surface of a sphere. Spheres decorated with possible solutions for n = 10, 11, 13 and 14 were calculated. The following STL files are provided: Solution_Sphere_N11.stl
Convex_Hull_N11.stl
Convex_Hull_Dual_N11.stl The image at the left shows printed versions of these files. The stl files are in Thomson_polyhedra_stl.zip.
All the SCAD files and the FORTRAN program used to make the polyhedron commands are in Thomson_polyhedra_programs.zip.

Solution_Sphere_N11.stl needs external support.  The other two files should be oriented so that a face rests on the build platform.  They can be printed with or without a raft.
For those who wish to convert additional solutions to polyhedron commands Thomson_polyhedra_programs.zip contains a readme.txt with some instructions and more information.

X Stop switch extender.

After upgrading to the E3D v6 I found that my nozzle was now off centre. Easiest way to combat this and retain full bed use was to move all of the stops. This shifts the X stop to the right to compensate for the change of location of the E3D v6 with Bowden setup from this design > http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1632847. I really like this design for its great simplicity and visibility of hot end, good job Tech2C. I modified the original as my x-carriage only used 3 linear bearings, a later model modification i think.

If anyone is interested I modified the other stop locations in the following way;

Z stop :- moved this down by drilling new holes for its original holder about 7mm below the lowest point of the original locator slots.

Y stop :- I didn't actually move the stop but the bed itself by shifting the linear bearing blocks back so they they are on the wrong holes effectively moving the whole bed forward by the spacing of the bearing block holes (that just happened to be the right amount). This does mean that I only have 2 screws in each block now but it hasn't caused any problems.

title: Compass Knob Button for Monoprice Select Mini

description.text:
My MP Select Mini is my first 3D printer, and as you already know, the original knob button is really unusable. So after giving a shot to the Better Dial by auralgasm and its successor, I felt that something was missing, and is the ability to use the dial with one finger (iPod Classic users remember?) as sometimes when the base is all the way forward, using the dial with two fingers can be difficult.

So, after some thinking, sketching and a couple of prototypes, I came up with this design. Given the small diameter, I added a small fin that serves as a guide allowing to spin the knob with one finger. At the same time I kept the increased height with a texture that improves the grip and resembles some knobs from vintage audio systems and consoles.

Given my lack of expertise with 3D software, I used Tinkercad, so maybe is not the most sophisticated thing you can find around. But as my first contribution, I feel very good about it.

I added some pictures showing how to pull off the original knob, so you can have a better idea of the process to replace it.

Please let me know if the hole at the bottom is too tight to upload an update with a bigger hole (personally I prefer it tight, as it's a movable part that is in constant use).

UPDATE 1 I just learned that depending on the printing resolution (among other factors) the measurements can vary, so I'll upload a version with a wider bottom hole for a lower resolution in case someone want to print it at ~0.175 layer height.

UPDATE 2 I just uploaded a low resolution version with a sightly wider bottom hole, so to differentiate the files and their proper print resolution take in consideration the following:

  • MPSM - Compass Knob Button - HiRes.stl = 0.04375mm layer height
  • MPSM - Compass Knob Button - LoRes.stl = ~0.175mm layer height

Please let me know how it works for you.

title: JGAurora A3 Above Printer Spool Holder

description.text:
All required parts to make a spool holder for use above your JGAurora A3 3D Printer. Takes a little while to print, but it's really worth it. This will hold one, two, and/or three rolls of your favorite color filament above your printer (depending on width of spools), making it easier for your printer to pull filament and ensuring your prints to be better looking, more precise, and just freaking awesome!

After printing and putting together, be sure to let your filament drape OVER your spool instead of under it. DO NOT use a filament clip or filament guide as that will cause a bind between the spool and your print head.

When I changed from having my spools behind the printer and now have them above the printer, I have noticed that the lines in the prints have become a lot less noticeable. It seems having the spools above the printer take a lot of stress off the filament feed motor no matter the amount of stress from the spring loaded lever.

Printer:

JGAurora

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

.25

Notes:

I would use a raft on the dowel since it is slender and tall. All the other parts, no rafts are needed. I printed the parts with a 25% infill and haven't had any problems. To completely make this project, you will need to print the following:

1 - 15mm_dowel_165mm_long.stl
2 - Filament Spool Leveler.stl
1 - sides_for_spool_holder.stl

The sides will bump into the display board when placed behind it but will still fit without issue. You can set the whole filament holder to the left of the display if you are worried of damaging the board. You can cut back some of the print time if you want to chop the filament spool leveler down a bit. I use several different brands of filament and actually need the sizes it gives me.

To assemble:

On a flat surface (until you are used to it) place the dowel standing up. Place one side of the spool holder on it, then one of the spool levelers. Now place your filament spool on it. Next place another spool leveler, spool holder and push the round dowel clip down to tighten the assembly. Make sure that the openings at the bottom of the spool holders are facing the same direction.

title: Dial Gauge Mount extruder motor MP Maker Select v2

description.text:
This is a snap together dial gauge mounting bracket for my Monoprice Maker Select v2.1 so it should work well for any number of Wanhoo Duplicator i3 clones...

I was tired of using the standard bed leveling process and decided to go through pages of auto-level, feeler gauge leveling, and dial gauge leveling. I wasn't happy with any of the existing mounting options for a dial gauge and the selection for the Maker Select was quite limited. I liked the induction sensor mounted location off the right side extruder motor but only one for a dial gauge existed in my search, may be more now, and the dial was facing to the right.

I created this so that the dial faced forward. The two pieces fit together pretty snug but a drop of super glue will hold them together if they should loosen over time. The square (fan) portion attaches on the motor and the round (gauge) portion around the dial gauge. On my dial gauge off Amazon, Neoteck DTI Digital Dial Indicator 0.01/.0005'' Digital Probe Indicator Dial Test Gauge Range 0-25.4mm/1'' Dial Test Indicators Electronic Indicator Gauge, I have just under 2mm of clearance when zeroed on full extension. So there is at most 2mm of possible collision with the print. I use a twist tie to hold the feeler up if I think it will hit the print.

title: Electronics case (RAMPS/Arduino) for RepRapGuru Prusa i3 v2

description.text:
This is a case/enclosure for the electronics and wires for the RepRapGuru Prusa i3 v2. It may or may not work with other acrylic frame printers.
The case works well with a panel-mount USB cable, like this one:
http://www.ebay.com/itm/50cm-Right-Angle-USB-2-0-B-Male-to-USB-B-Female-Socket-Panel-Extension-Cable-USA-/351853664294?hash=item51ec1cd826:g:nR8AAOSwLF1X6NqC
This gives the printer a proper USB port.

Step 1

All those messy wires! Time to clean those up. First things first, turn off you printer. Then disconnect the LCD board from the RAMPS board.

Step 2

Unscrew the RAMPS/Arduino from the acrylic frame. Store the nuts somewhere safe.

Step 3

Throw away the nylon spacers. The printed case will be serving this purpose.

Step 4

If you have any wires coming through the hole highlighted in the photo, disconnect them from the RAMPS/Arduino.

Step 5

Move the electronics boards and wires out of the way.

Step 6

Put the back of the case in place, and feed the wires through the hole shown in the photo. The back of the case should be flush with the acrylic frame. In the photo, my measurements for the large bolt were off and I needed to cut a larger hole in the case; I've since corrected this.

Step 7

Reconnect the wires you disconnected earlier. Screw the RAMPS/Arduino boards onto the acrylic frame, securing the case to the frame as well. Careful not to tighten the nuts too much.

Step 8

If you bought the panel mount USB cable, connect it to the Arduino and screw the other end to the case using whatever spare screws and nuts you have. If you didn't buy the panel mount USB cable, a regular cable can go through the case at the hole shown in the photo or in one of the holes at the top of the case.

Step 9

Disconnect the z-axis end stop cable, feed it through the hole in the front of the case, and reconnect the cable.

Step 10

Reconnect the LCD board and start organizing those wires! The top of the case has three spots for wires to enter the case. The slot on the left is meant for long wires coming from the extruder assembly, the middle hole is meant for shorter extruder assembly wires and ribbon cables from the LCD board, and the right hole is meant for wires coming from the heated bed. You may want to use twist ties to secure the wires to the case, making it easier to get the wires to stay inside the case.

Step 11

Put the front of the case on. The three clips will hold the front in place while you find some screws. Make sure the wall sticking out of the back of the case (highlighted in green) rests between the two rails on the front of the case.

Step 12

Add screws. I used US #6 sized screws, 3/4" long. The holes should be narrow enough that the screw threads bite into the plastic.

Step 13

Turn your printer on and make everything still works!

2017-06-03

Updated the back of the case to be less prone to slicing errors. If you use Repetier-Host, I suggest either slicing with CuraEngine, or if you slice with slic3r, repair the model before slicing.

For those in need of a letter scale.
I really like the real-world-use-things and couldn't find a letter scale on thingiverse. Thought about adding a scale, but it will be too dependant on printer settings, material and counter weights, so just use a (semi-) permanent marker for this. For the small scale I used mr alligator as a letter holder: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:13612
Had to "fix" it using Netfabb before I could import it in OpenSCAD. I've also uploaded a version2, the largest I can get it with my 180x200mm buildplate. I've made three stl's with all the parts to print.
The black & yellow scale is version 2. I recommend to make the weighing platform a little thinner, so it won't need as much counterweights. Made it a work in progress again, I think it's better to shorten the arms holding the letter plate.
I would like the big scale to be good for 250 grams.
Make the scale more stable by moving the foot to the heavy side. For the final version 3 I added some stability by moving the legs to the heavy side of the scale and making them bigger. I added another arm to hold counterweights so these are balanced. Smaller connecting arms so it can take more weight, but also makes it much more stable.

Print, assemble and calibrate, You can print the parts seperate using the .scad file or print the build plate (173 x 173 mm).
I used pieces of 3mm PLA for the rod connections, fixed them on side using a solder iron, other side push fit.
I used an m3 bolt to mount two M8 nuts as counterweights and an m5 bolt to use as an adjustment screw.
For the big ones I used four 608ZZ Bearings as counterweights.

description.text:
I created a counter weight box that mounts to the x axis using the tensioner screws/bolts.
It is designed to hold 4 stacks of pennies (25-28 pennies high each) on their sides to give an equivalent weight to the stepper motor on the other side of the X-axis.
The box has a hole in it to allow you to run an allen wrench to the adjustment screw.

In theory, having equal weight on both sides of the X axis should help keep the Z axis motors synchronized. Both should see an equivalent amount of weight and the threaded nuts should also stay on the same part of the threaded rods on both sides.

I also remixed the original tensioner to fit a 9mm wide toothed pulley.

title: LWC Nintendo Switch Single Joycon Grip " Phantom"

description.text:
Found a great base model from 3DBotMaker, it was pretty nice but I had to modify it after my needs.

first of all I wanted a more comfortable grip for bigger hands so I added two brackets on each side, it felt much better already, but then there was a problem with the joycon wire, it was kinda anoying standing out on top and I just didnt like that a lot, so I created a simple solution to integrate the wire into the grip, its out of the way and easy to insert or remove.

The joycon snapped in the original design quite well but as I printed it on another printer it was off about 1mm and the joycon was a bit lose. I created a spring loaded holding arm which holds the Joycon secure in place evenso the print doesnt fit the size of the joycon perfectly.

Phantoms wire management supports both Joycons ( left - and right + )

A pair of bigger and smaller sidegrips are included, depending on how big your hands are.

The name you ask?! well put it in front of your face and look in the mirror ;)

Requirements

You need a spring from a simple and cheap ball bearing pen. Place it in the spring cover and combine it with the holding arm, tadaaa you have a spring loaded holding arm now.

Use some glue or azetone ABS mixture to attach the springloaded arm+spring+spring cover to the back of the Phantom, of course only the outher parts of the spring cover are glued to the back, NOT the moving part in the middle.

Also the Sidegrips need to be glued on, I use a Acetone+ABS solution to do so, but if you haven not printed in ABS just use some superglue or similar.

The spring arm is preloaded so dont worry if there is some tension when you glue it to the back, its ment to be that way.

description.text:
While writing MAKE: Soft Robotics, I've discovered I need more hands than I actually own to properly document all of the projects I've been developing. I built this plywood camera arm and foot switch to try and extend my project documentation powers.

You can find photos and videos of the cutting, finishing, assembly, and final thing here. You can also find some more project notes here.

I designed this in SolidWorks, cut it out on a ShopBot with a 1/4" endmill, and finished it with shellac. The arm works well, though I have a few edits I'd make to it if I had to do it all over again - tightening up the tolerances on the friction fits and giving it longer lever arms on the upper screw handles, but I'm very happy with the results despite.

You don't need SolidWorks to build your own camera arm based on these files, but you'll likely have to do some shimming or sanding on the friction fits and mortise and tenon joints if you aren't able to adjust the CAD for the specific thickness of plywood you end up with. Since plywood is a natural material, no two sheets are ever quite the same.

Also, before you post in all caps in the comments, I know I'm mixing metric and imperial, here. I tend to work in metric fasteners in my shop, so have them on hand. However, I live and work in the great US of A, so the Imperial system is unavoidable. You're smart folks. I know you can keep it straight. If you have trouble, Google can convert measurements automatically, now.

Bill of Materials

  • 1/2 sheet of 3/4" plywood (high quality veneer ply for best results) x 1
    Lumberyards or home improvement stores - $30-50

  • Freud 04-110 1/4" Diameter by 1" Double Flute Straight Router Bit with 1/4" Shank x 2
    Amazon.com - $12.99

  • Pixel Wired Remote Shutter Release Control compatible with NIKON MC-DC2, for NIKON Nikon D7000 D5100 D5000 D3200 D3100 D90 x 1
    Amazon.com - $7.15

  • Uxcell Foot Pedal Switch x 1
    Amazon.com - $5.86

  • Breeze Power-Seal Stainless Steel Hose Clamp, Worm-Drive, SAE Size 28, 1-5/16" to 2-1/4" Diameter Range, 1/2" Bandwidth x Pack of 10
    Amazon.com - $8.80

  • Zinc-Plated Iron Wing Head Thumb Screw
    M6 Thread, 1mm Pitch, 25mm Long x 1
    McMaster #92595A409 - $2.70

  • 18-8 Stainless Steel Hex Head Screw
    M6 x 1 mm Thread, 80 mm Long, Partially Threaded x Pack of 10
    McMaster #91287A254 - $5.72

  • Zinc-Plated Steel Wing Nut
    Class 5, M6 x 1 mm Thread x Pack of 25
    McMaster #94300A330 - $5.55

  • Black-Oxide Steel Knurled Head Thumb Screw
    Low Head, 1/4"-20 Thread, 1" Long x 1
    McMaster #90200A547 - $3.28

  • Zinc-Plated Steel Tee Nut Inserts for Wood
    M6 x 1 mm Thread Size, 9 mm Long x Pack of 50
    McMaster #98965A310 - $8.90

  • Black-Oxide Alloy Steel Hex Drive Flat Head Screw
    M6 x 1 mm Thread, 50 mm Long x Pack of 25
    McMaster #91294A250 - $8.24

  • Zinc-Plated Steel Wing Nut
    Class 5, M6 x 1 mm Thread x Pack of 25
    McMaster #94300A330 - $5.55

Instructions

SolidWorks

  • Download all of the files on this thing into the same folder and open up "camera_arm_01.SLDASM" in SolidWorks
  • This should open up the master assembly with all the referenced files - if not, go hunting and fix those broken links
  • Adjust the variable that sets the plywood thickness according to the thickness of the 3/4" plywood you have on hand (individual sheets vary quite a bit)
  • Export a vector file from the SW drawing, and do your path planning in your favorite CAM tool

ShopBot

  • The "camera_arm_01a.AI" and "camera_arm_01.crv" files were made for a ShopBot with a 4' x 8' cutting area using a 1/4" router bit - if that doesn't suit your machine you'll need to rework the path planning in your CAM tool
  • The work holding for this process involved screwing down the plywood sheet to the spoilboard, cutting all the straight holes and interior pockets, putting screws into those holes to hold down individual components, and then milling the exterior cuts. Some of the components needed bridges to prevent them from rotating during cutting

Assembly

  • Test fit all parts to make certain nothing needs to be recut
  • The friction fit parts at the top and bottom of the arm use the pipe clamps to attach together. The lower ones work well, but the coupling that is attached to the wall mounting component is a little stiff. If I were to do everything over again, I'd make the slot that fits those parts together tighter and the relief cut that allows the pieces to flex a little longer
  • Knock the M6 bolts into the screw handles until the heads are flush with the wood, and then glue on the round pieces that accompany those parts (as seen at the top of this image)
  • The camera arm is mounted to the wall in my shop using 1/4"-20 threaded rod and drywall toggle bolts. It was originally designed for standard drywall anchors and screws, but these ended up being too short to bite into my shop's odd vintage walls
  • The 6.8mm holes in the arm components are for the threaded tee nut inserts. Knock them in with a hammer
  • The camera arm initially had a hard time staying in a position without sagging, so I added rubber pads to the joints that slipped to give it some more staying power. This helped a ton. I would like to redo some of the screw knobs to be more like a handle with a longer arm to increase the torque I can apply to the joints that bear the most weight
  • The part that mounts to the swivel plate (at the top of this photo) will need to be cut square so it can attach flush to the swivel plate itself. That was an oversight on my part. Also, that component doesn't use a wing nut for the joint, but a threaded insert
  • The wing nut-headed bolt attaches to the small laser cut component that's generated by "delrin_screw_clip_01.AI", which goes on the end of the camera arm to secure any camera with a 1/4"-20 screw mount. I used a sheet of 1/8" delrin for the clip, but you could use just about any flexible plastic, and even cut the part out by hand. It's just there to accept a little rubber pad to help the camera clamp down and keep the screw from falling out of the camera arm

Foot Switch

  • I hacked a foot switch together with a shutter release for my camera after my camera remote control started acting up
  • The original shutter release is simple as heck - three wires connected to three metal strips. When the first strip touches the second, it completes one circuit, and when they both touch the third, it completes both circuits. For the camera to take a photo, it needs the first and second circuits to be closed in sequence
  • I duplicated this design inside of the foot pedal by glueing a pair of microswitches (like you'd find as the limit switches in a laser cutter or 3d printer) together, wiring them like the metal strips in the shutter release, and adding a strip of plastic to the foot pedal's housing so one switch would go off before the other

title: Modular "Watch Band" EyeX Mount (for VESA & More)

description.text:
This mount holds a Tobii EyeX Eye Gaze camera directly under the monitor and maintains its orientation.

Walk-through here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lR-zV6_k1IM&feature=youtu.be

Mounting an eye gaze device correctly is critical for those who use it to control their computer and to communicate. One challenge is that the monitor sometimes must be rotated to match the user's orientation (in a bed, power chair, etc.). Many mounts for eye gaze cameras will fail when rotated, or will remain parallel to the ground (which doesn't work).

This mount uses a "Watch Band" linkage to allow the user to move the device while maintaining the critical orientations. The holes are 4mm in diameter, and a metric M4 x 70mm pan-head screw will work perfectly. You can follow our progress on this project at the ATMakers Facebook Group:
https://www.facebook.com/groups/ATMakers/

Here's a walk-through of it mounted.
https://www.facebook.com/bill.binko/videos/1377778868931833/?permPage=1

This will be part of a larger Guide at the main ATMakers.org site and we will update this when it's ready.

Notes:

Printing is pretty simple. Flat orientation w/supports for the screw holes is what I ended up with (we tried several with varying degrees of success - look at the pix). Whatever setup you have for flat parts w/holes will work.

We printed in PLA, but I intend to use PETG for the ones I'm sending to a user just to get the most strength. I will update when that's done.

Assembly

I used M4 x 70mm machine screws (Pan-Head - tapered heads will crack the PLA - see photos). Here's a link to the ones I bought at Lowes:
https://www.lowes.com/pd/The-Hillman-Group-4-Count-4mm-to-0-7-x-60mm-Pan-Head-Zinc-Plated-Metric-Machine-Screws/999994912

I used one washer inside the joint, but you may not need it. Friction of the threads should hold the weight of the device.

You can watch the ideation & initial prototype in this video. If you like it, join the group!

https://www.facebook.com/groups/ATMakers/permalink/286819688396144/

There are several ways to print this standee. The first is to use the GH_Monster_bot_num_x-10 and the GH_Monster_top_num. These will snap fit together. Print the bottom at .1mm and 80%+ infill. This is to make the numbers sharp and the axle strong so it won't snap off. The top can be printed at .2mm and 30% infill.

The second way to print is with GH_Monster_bot_plain (or with riser). This is also a snap fit. This allows you to write on the bottom, or print out on paper the numbers and glue it on. Base the GH_Monster_top_narrow for small lettering and the GH_Monster_top_num for larger lettering.

The last way is to print with a disk in the middle. Use the GH_Monster_bot_plain_disk and either the GH_Monster_disk_numext_x-10 or plain. Choose the appropriate top. Glue the top part of the axle to the top piece. Don't get any glue on the disk.

Both tops have a standee gap of 2.2mm. This has been tested to work well with Gloomhaven standees.

title: Hot Melt Injection Mold for Maker Faire Robot

description.text:
Update (7/1/17): Turns out this design is nearly identical to an earlier design: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:796654 which another user just brought to my attention. Check it out, too!

This is a test of a mold for hot melt glue injection molding. I'm not sure if it is good for anything, but I wanted to see if it is possible to injection mold hot melt glue in a PLA printed mold. (It is!) I started off with the iconic Maker Faire robot (the manos arriba version) and created a 2-part mold. I added an inlet port and outlet ports at the extremities.To keep from melting the input port with the hot melt glue gun nozzle, I also designed a small sacrificial input duct that does get a little melted, but it is easily replaced. I was worried that the hot melt glue would simply melt the mold, but even though I was using high-temp hot glue (the gun gets to about 220C) the mold survived fine.

The only use I can think of for this technique would be for over-molding/potting of electronic components or small circuit boards.

Printer Brand:

MakerGear

Printer:

MakerGear M2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

I printed this with zero solid bottom layers (as shown in the photo). This is because I wanted to dunk the filled mold in water to cool it off before the PLA melted, and the open mesh of the infill allows the cooling water to get right up next to the mold surface.

I printed the mold show in the photo at 150% scale, although I also did an earlier version at 100%.

Using the Mold

First, I coated the inside of the mold very thoroughly with oil to act as a release agent. Then I clamped the two halves together in a vice and placed the sacrificial duct on top of the input port. Next, I jammed the tip of the hot melt glue gun into the tapered duct piece and injected glue until I saw it start to ooze out of the outlet ports. Finally, I dunked the whole mold in a tub of water for 15 min to make sure the glue had fully hardened.

To retrieve the molded object, I first pried the two mold halves apart with knife blade, and then also used the tip of the blade to pry the object out of the mold. It takes a little patience because you don't want to rip his arms or legs off.

title: Raspberry Pi Camera Mount for MP Select Mini

description.text:
This mount allows you to attach Raspberry Pi camera directly to the bed of Monoprice Select Mini, for a great videos/timelapses and monitoring the progress of your prints.

Raspberry Pi Camera is significantly lighter than, for example, GoPro, so it won't put much strain on the bed/stepper motor. Also, many of us already have a Raspberry Pi running OctoPrint, so this is an easy addition.

See a video of the mount in use:
http://youtu.be/EGkVbrJnm24

Note that there are 2 alternative camera mounts: one directly for the Raspberry Pi and one for a camera case I had (link below), and decided to make one mount for it too - for those of us that prefer the camera to be enclosed. Both designs have been tested.

Requirements:

  • Raspberry Pi (1/2/3/anything that runs OctoPrint/OctoPi)
  • Raspberry Pi Camera (V1 or V2, Note: I only have V1 thus I haven't tried with V2 myself, I'm hoping it should work as well as the size seems to be same)
  • longer camera cable: http://amzn.to/2BcbkQm
  • M3 screws and M2 spacers

Optional:

  • Camera case: http://amzn.to/2Di9DCA

In most cases you'll need to print only those 3 pars:

  • bed mount
  • arm (use longer or shorter depending on the preference of camera angle)
  • camera mount

I had the above camera case available, thus the "camera housing mount" is designed to fit with this particular element, if you happen to have it too and would prefer to use it instead of the open "camera mount".

If you want to make your own element to hold the camera (i.e. for any other camera case), here are the tab dimensions, to allow seamless joining with the arm:

  • tab length: 12mm
  • tab height: 10mm
  • tab thickness: 2mm
  • tab spacing: 2.55mm (note: this is space between tabs, not the pitch, and is slightly larger than tab thickness to allow easy fitting)
  • M3 hole diameter: 3.75mm
  • fillet at the end of the tab: 6mm (half of the tab length, so it's completely round)
    *** bed and camera housing mounts have 2 tabs (prongs?) in a joint, the arm has 3 tabs for joint on each side

Moreover, provided is a test pieces for the joints. Please feel free to use it for your remakes for a quicker development :)

To make sure the joints fit nicely with your print settings, you can print the "camera housing mount" and "joint for test" files, and then check the fitting. If it's correct, print the remaining parts.

Screws required for assembly:

  • M3x8mm - quantity: 4 (4 screws, 4 nuts)
  • M3x16mm - quantity: 2 (2 screws, 2 nuts)
  • M2 spacers, screws, nuts - quantity: 4 pairs (to attach the camera to the mount)

If you don't have those, they can be easily purchased i.e. on Amazon: -

  • M3 and M2 screws: http://amzn.to/2BedXBb
  • M2 spacers (stand-offs): http://amzn.to/2ESzcL1
    Those are the exact sets I use, thus I guarantee the required sizes are in those sets.

No drilling required, and it screws right onto the bed, which happens to have conveniently located holes. It doesn't collide with the base as bed moves, with fan/hot end, x/y gantry, doesn't come in the way of linear bearings under the bed - I checked it all :)

And mounting camera this way makes time-lapses significantly better: instead of bed jumping back and forth (as is the case with cameras mounted to the base instead of bed, or standing next to the printer), you can actually see the product being constructed.

Great for use with OctoPrint!

[Updated on 4/23/2017]: I re-uploaded updated version of the "bed mount" - considering that there are various M3 screws out there, with varying head heights, I moved the tabs a little higher to minimize the risk of scratching the base.

[Updated on 4/30/2017]: Added short arm - about half the length of the original arm. Makes for a more compact package, and provide slightly better view of the printed object.

Note: if the footage from your Raspberry Pi camera appears blurry, you can adjust the focus by screwing the lens - there's even a dedicated tool to do that. Quick search will tell you everything :)

Enjoy!

For more projects, please visit my personal blog:
http://www.BogdanBerg.com/

Printer:

Monoprice Select Mini

Resolution:

0.15 mm layer height

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Print orientation:

  • arm (long or short) - lying on the back,
  • bed mount - needs support, since there's a small notch that goes under the bed,
  • camera mount - lying on the front face
  • (optional) camera housing mount - lying flat, not on the side

I recommend doing a test print to make sure the joints fit nicely with your settings (use the "camera housing" and "joint only for test" files.

I printed it in PLA and is seems plenty strong.

Attach the camera using M2 spacers

Simply attach the camera to the backing plate/mount.

I used 6mm nylon spacers, but their length here is not critical.

Note that you need to guide the camera cable through the slit in the mount - to unplug the cable from camera, pull out the tabs from the port gently.

Then reassemble, making sure the cable orientation is correct (the visible leads on the cable should be facing the front of the camera - in other words, you should see the leads as on the same side as the camera lens).

Connect the 3 pieces printed pieces using M3 screws

Screws required:

  • M3x8mm - quantity: 4 (4 screws, 4 nuts)
  • M3x16mm - quantity: 2 (2 screws, 2 nuts)

I recommend screwing the bed mount to the bed first, then attaching camera to the backing plate, and in the end connecting it all with the arm.

After aligning the angle of the camera, tighten the screws (but not too much, it will stay in place without excessive force) so everything stays in place.

I made this on my second day of owning my first 3D printer :) At the same time, didn't want it to be rushed, so the design has been printed few times and verified (using both alternate components: part that attaches camera directly, as well as the camera housing mount).

Designed in Fusion 360, few test prints to finalize various details, tested with the Raspberry Pi camera to verify the viewing angle/distance to printer components to avoid any unpleasant surprises (the camera won't collide with any of the printer elements, and it also provides plenty of room for removal of the prints).
